{"title_page": "Anthony Sims", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{Primary sources|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American artist}}\n\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Anthony Sims\n| style = [[Neo-Expressionism]]\n| birth_name = Robert Anthony Sims\n| nationality = [[Mexican-American]]\n| image = Self Portrait by Anthony Sims.jpg\n| caption = Sims in 2020.\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1998|10|11}}\n| known_for = [[Painting]]\n| movement = \n| alt = \n| website = https://asimsart.com\n| birth_place = [[Southaven, Mississippi]]\n}}\n\n'''Robert Anthony Sims''' (born October 11, 1998) is a [[Mexican Americans|Mexican-American]] fine artist, photographer, and [[Experimental music|producer]] from [[Memphis, Tennessee]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.memphiscurrent.com/product-page/memphis-current-issue-no-3|title=Memphis Current Issue No 3|last=|first=|date=|website=Memphis Current Magazine|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sims is known for his high-energy colors that display raw human expression.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127111937/https://www.lovechaosmagazine.com/winter-2019/an-artist-who-perseveres-the-story-of-a-sims|title=An Artist Like You: The life of Anthony Sims \u2014 Love & Chaos Magazine|last=|first=|date=2020-01-27|website=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sims has been featured in [[Vogue Italia]] and has works in multiple museum permanent collections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmoda.org/asimsart|title=Anthony Sims|website=MMoDA|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.it/en/photovogue/portfolio/?id=222084|title=Anthony Sims - Vogue Italia|last=|first=|date=|website=Vogue Italia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Fine arts ===\nRobert Anthony Sims emerged into the underground [[digital art]] scene in 2017 as \"Pygeon\" an acronym that stands for \"Probably your greatest example of nothing.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremelegends.com/single-post/2017/10/12/Memphis-artist-Pygeon-is-on-an-intriguing-mission|title=Memphis' artist Pygeon is on an intriguing mission!|website=Supreme Legends {{!}} I Think, I Make, I Create|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Sims' first project in 2017 was titled \"Poetry Complex\" and was a [[mixtape]] themed series of artworks with poetry on each piece.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremelegends.com/single-post/2017/12/01/Robert-Sims-expresses-his-view-of-art-in-pop-culture-today-in-Poetry-Complex|title=Robert Sims expresses his view of art in pop culture today with 'Poetry Complex'|website=Supreme Legends {{!}} I Think, I Make, I Create|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> \n\nIn 2018, Sims started [[Graffiti|tagging]] in downtown Memphis and created his logo known as \"FACE.\" Once Sims' work emerged into the art scene of Memphis, he was featured in [[The Pinch|The Pinch Journal]] as a featured artist.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=May|first=Jonathan Owen|date=|title=SPRING 2019 (39.1)|url=http://www.pinchjournal.com/pinch-issues/2019/4/30/5dtl7jxlj2enmitmuw7jsy3a80w3lw|journal=[[The Pinch]]|publisher=[[University of Memphis]]|volume=39|pages=11-112,159|via=}}</ref> \n\nSims became a member of [[Steve Kaufman]]'s \"American Pop Art collection\" in [[New York City]] in October of 2019.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.americanpopartinc.com/a-sims.htm|title=Artist: Anthony Sims|last=Vachier|first=Diana|date=|website=American Pop Art Collective by Steve Kaufman|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn 2020, the [[Memphis Flyer]] wrote about a collective show presented by Anthony Sims at Stock&Belle Gallery in Memphis, TN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/artist-reception-for-manufactured-studios/Event?oid=22508146|title=Artist reception by Anthony Sims|last=|first=|date=|website=Memphis Flyer|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> \n\n=== Photography ===\nSims film photograph taken in 2020 and titled \"1980's Glam\" was published in [[Vogue Italia]]'s magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.it/en/photovogue/Portfolio/Archive?photographer=A.%20Sims&md_pageIndex=0&md_page=0&md_pid=2288844|title=Archive - PhotoVogue - Vogue|website=www.vogue.it|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Musical projects ===\nSims illustrated many musical covers for other artist, including most prominently \"Long Flights\" by NugLife and [[Issa Gold]] in 2019.<ref>{{Citation|title=Nuglife (Ft. Issa Gold) \u2013 Long Flights|url=https://genius.com/Nuglife-long-flights-lyrics|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\nIn 2020, Sims worked on the project \"No New Friends\" by NugLife and [[Yung Simmie]] which came out January 13, 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.manufacturedstudios.com/post/artist-anthony-sims-joins-hiphop|title=Artist Anthony Sims joins hiphop.|date=|work=Manufactured Magazine|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Nuglife (Ft. Yung Simmie) \u2013 No New Friends|url=https://genius.com/Nuglife-no-new-friends-lyrics|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Selected collections ==\n\n* [[Manufactured Museum of Digital Art]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmoda.org/collection-artist|title=Collection-Artist|website=MMoDA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n*[[Meridian Museum of Art]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.meridianmuseum.org/|title=Meridian Museum Archive|last=|first=|date=|website=www.meridianmuseum.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n*American Pop Art by [[Steve Kaufman]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[https://www.asimsart.com Official website]\n{{Commons category|Anthony Sims}}<br />{{US-painter-stub}}\n\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:People from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Artists from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:21st-century painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n__INDEX__\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{Primary sources|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American artist}}\n\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Anthony Sims\n| style = [[Expressionism]], [[dadaism]], and [[primitivism]]\n| birth_name = Robert Anthony Sims\n| nationality = [[Mexican-American]]\n| image = Self Portrait by Anthony Sims.jpg\n| caption = Sims in 2020.\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1998|10|11}}\n| known_for = [[Painting]]\n| movement = \n| alt = \n| website = https://asimsart.com\n| birth_place = [[Southaven, Mississippi]]\n}}\n\n'''Robert Anthony Sims''' (born October 11, 1998) is a [[Mexican Americans|Mexican-American]] fine artist, photographer, and [[Experimental music|producer]] from [[Memphis, Tennessee]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.memphiscurrent.com/product-page/memphis-current-issue-no-3|title=Memphis Current Issue No 3|last=|first=|date=|website=Memphis Current Magazine|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sims is known for his high-energy colors that display raw human expression.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127111937/https://www.lovechaosmagazine.com/winter-2019/an-artist-who-perseveres-the-story-of-a-sims|title=An Artist Like You: The life of Anthony Sims \u2014 Love & Chaos Magazine|last=|first=|date=2020-01-27|website=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sims has been featured in [[Vogue Italia]] and has works in multiple museum permanent collections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmoda.org/asimsart|title=Anthony Sims|website=MMoDA|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.it/en/photovogue/portfolio/?id=222084|title=Anthony Sims - Vogue Italia|last=|first=|date=|website=Vogue Italia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Fine arts ===\nRobert Anthony Sims emerged into the underground [[digital art]] scene in 2017 as \"Pygeon\" an acronym that stands for \"Probably your greatest example of nothing.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremelegends.com/single-post/2017/10/12/Memphis-artist-Pygeon-is-on-an-intriguing-mission|title=Memphis' artist Pygeon is on an intriguing mission!|website=Supreme Legends {{!}} I Think, I Make, I Create|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Sims' first project in 2017 was titled \"Poetry Complex\" and was a [[mixtape]] themed series of artworks with poetry on each piece.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremelegends.com/single-post/2017/12/01/Robert-Sims-expresses-his-view-of-art-in-pop-culture-today-in-Poetry-Complex|title=Robert Sims expresses his view of art in pop culture today with 'Poetry Complex'|website=Supreme Legends {{!}} I Think, I Make, I Create|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> \n\nIn 2018, Sims started [[Graffiti|tagging]] in downtown Memphis and created his logo known as \"FACE.\" Once Sims' work emerged into the art scene of Memphis, he was featured in [[The Pinch|The Pinch Journal]] as a featured artist.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=May|first=Jonathan Owen|date=|title=SPRING 2019 (39.1)|url=http://www.pinchjournal.com/pinch-issues/2019/4/30/5dtl7jxlj2enmitmuw7jsy3a80w3lw|journal=[[The Pinch]]|publisher=[[University of Memphis]]|volume=39|pages=11-112,159|via=}}</ref> \n\nSims became a member of [[Steve Kaufman]]'s \"American Pop Art collection\" in [[New York City]] in October of 2019.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.americanpopartinc.com/a-sims.htm|title=Artist: Anthony Sims|last=Vachier|first=Diana|date=|website=American Pop Art Collective by Steve Kaufman|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn 2020, the [[Memphis Flyer]] wrote about a collective show presented by Anthony Sims at Stock&Belle Gallery in Memphis, TN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/artist-reception-for-manufactured-studios/Event?oid=22508146|title=Artist reception by Anthony Sims|last=|first=|date=|website=Memphis Flyer|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> \n\n=== Photography ===\nSims film photograph taken in 2020 and titled \"1980's Glam\" was published in [[Vogue Italia]]'s magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.it/en/photovogue/Portfolio/Archive?photographer=A.%20Sims&md_pageIndex=0&md_page=0&md_pid=2288844|title=Archive - PhotoVogue - Vogue|website=www.vogue.it|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Musical projects ===\nSims illustrated many musical covers for other artist, including most prominently \"Long Flights\" by NugLife and [[Issa Gold]] in 2019.<ref>{{Citation|title=Nuglife (Ft. Issa Gold) \u2013 Long Flights|url=https://genius.com/Nuglife-long-flights-lyrics|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\nIn 2020, Sims worked on the project \"No New Friends\" by NugLife and [[Yung Simmie]] which came out January 13, 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.manufacturedstudios.com/post/artist-anthony-sims-joins-hiphop|title=Artist Anthony Sims joins hiphop.|date=|work=Manufactured Magazine|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Nuglife (Ft. Yung Simmie) \u2013 No New Friends|url=https://genius.com/Nuglife-no-new-friends-lyrics|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Selected collections ==\n\n* [[Manufactured Museum of Digital Art]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmoda.org/collection-artist|title=Collection-Artist|website=MMoDA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n*[[Meridian Museum of Art]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.meridianmuseum.org/|title=Meridian Museum Archive|last=|first=|date=|website=www.meridianmuseum.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n*American Pop Art by [[Steve Kaufman]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[https://www.asimsart.com Official website]\n{{Commons category|Anthony Sims}}<br />{{US-painter-stub}}\n\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:People from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Artists from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:21st-century painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n__INDEX__\n", "name_user": "UndyingCarrot", "label": "safe", "comment": "further cleaned", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthony_Sims"}
{"title_page": "Saud bin Abdul-Aziz bin Muhammad bin Saud", "text_new": "{{short description|19th-century ruler of the House of Saud}}\n{{Refimprove|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox noble|head\n| name = Saud II bin Abdul Aziz Al Saud\n| title = Saud II\n| succession =  Abdullah ibn Saud\n| noble family = [[House of Saud]]\n| issue = \n*[[Abdullah bin Saud|Abdullah]]\n*[[Khalid bin Saud|Khalid]]\n*Mishari\n*Faisal\n}}\n'''Imam Saud II al Kabeer bin Abdul-Aziz bin Muhammad Al-Saud''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062b\u0627\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0628\u064a\u0631 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632  \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0622\u0644 \u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f}}) (d. 1814) ruled the [[First Saudi State]] from 1803 to 1814. During his rule, Saud annexed Mecca and Medina from the Ottoman Empire.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Khatab |first1=Sayed |date=2011 |title=Understanding Islamic Fundamentalism: The Theological and Ideological Basis of Al-Qa'ida's Political Tactics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KBYnDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA74 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9789774164996 |accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Kingship==\nThe [[House of Saud]] extended its rule beyond the [[Najd]] and into the [[Hijaz]] which culminated with the capture of Makkah and Madinah. Saud's reign was a period of religious cleansing in [[Arabia]]. During his reign, attacks on shrines in [[Iraq]] continued.  The new Saudis cleansed the [[Kaaba]] in Mecca and destroyed the tombs of numerous men in Madinah.  This was in accordance with the Wahhabi desire to return [[Islam]] to its simple beginnings.  The forces of Saud also felt that they were emulating the example of [[Muhammad]] who smashed idols when he retook Mecca.\n\nThis religious cleansing did not sit well with other Muslims though.  Many other Muslims found the actions to be extreme, and were stunned that the holy cities had been taken so easily. The Ottoman Empire did not want to relent control over the cities to local tribesmen. The Ottomans could not retake the cities on their own though as the bulk of their forces was tied up in Europe. [[Mehemet Ali|Muhammad Ali]], the viceroy of [[Egypt]], was assigned to recapture the Arabian territories. One of his sons, commanding the Egyptian troops, succeeded in conquering the [[Hijaz]] in 1812.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box | before=[[Abdul-Aziz bin Muhammad bin Saud]] | title=Imam of [[First Saudi State]] | after=[[Abdullah bin Saud]] | years=1803\u20131814}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saud Ibn Abdul Aziz Ibn Muhammad Ibn Saud}}\n[[Category:1814 deaths]]\n[[Category:Arabs of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:House of Saud]]\n[[Category:People of the Wahhabi War]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n\n{{SaudiArabia-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|19th-century ruler of the House of Saud}}\n{{Refimprove|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox noble|head\n| name = Saud II bin Abdul Aziz Al Saud\n| title = '''Saud''' bin [[Abdul Aziz bin Muhammad bin Saud|Abdul-Aziz]] bin [[Muhammad bin Saud|Muhammad]] al Saud\n| succession =  Abdullah ibn Saud\n| noble family = [[House of Saud]]\n| issue = \n*[[Abdullah bin Saud|Abdullah]]\n*[[Khalid bin Saud|Khalid]]\n*Mishari\n*Faisal\n}}\n'''Imam Saud II al Kabeer bin Abdul-Aziz bin Muhammad Al-Saud''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062b\u0627\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0628\u064a\u0631 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632  \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0622\u0644 \u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f}}) (d. 1814) ruled the [[First Saudi State]] from 1803 to 1814. During his rule, Saud annexed Mecca and Medina from the Ottoman Empire.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Khatab |first1=Sayed |date=2011 |title=Understanding Islamic Fundamentalism: The Theological and Ideological Basis of Al-Qa'ida's Political Tactics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KBYnDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA74 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9789774164996 |accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Kingship==\nThe [[House of Saud]] extended its rule beyond the [[Najd]] and into the [[Hijaz]] which culminated with the capture of Makkah and Madinah. Saud's reign was a period of religious cleansing in [[Arabia]]. During his reign, attacks on shrines in [[Iraq]] continued.  The new Saudis cleansed the [[Kaaba]] in Mecca and destroyed the tombs of numerous men in Madinah.  This was in accordance with the Wahhabi desire to return [[Islam]] to its simple beginnings.  The forces of Saud also felt that they were emulating the example of [[Muhammad]] who smashed idols when he retook Mecca.\n\nThis religious cleansing did not sit well with other Muslims though.  Many other Muslims found the actions to be extreme, and were stunned that the holy cities had been taken so easily. The Ottoman Empire did not want to relent control over the cities to local tribesmen. The Ottomans could not retake the cities on their own though as the bulk of their forces was tied up in Europe. [[Mehemet Ali|Muhammad Ali]], the viceroy of [[Egypt]], was assigned to recapture the Arabian territories. One of his sons, commanding the Egyptian troops, succeeded in conquering the [[Hijaz]] in 1812.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box | before=[[Abdul-Aziz bin Muhammad bin Saud]] | title=Imam of [[First Saudi State]] | after=[[Abdullah bin Saud]] | years=1803\u20131814}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saud Ibn Abdul Aziz Ibn Muhammad Ibn Saud}}\n[[Category:1814 deaths]]\n[[Category:Arabs of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:House of Saud]]\n[[Category:People of the Wahhabi War]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n\n{{SaudiArabia-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Alhadramy Alkendy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saud_bin_Abdul-Aziz_bin_Muhammad_bin_Saud"}
